Document: Navigation Introduction 2D
Path: godot/tutorials/navigation/navigation_introduction_2d.rst
Summary: This document provides an overview of Godot's 2D navigation objects, classes, and servers, explaining their primary uses in game development.

Godot offers several objects, classes, and servers for 2D navigation and pathfinding.

Astar2D:
Provides an option to find the shortest path in a graph of weighted points. Best suited for cell-based 2D gameplay where actors only need to reach predefined, distinct positions rather than any position within an area.

AstarGrid2D:
A specialized variant of AStar2D for partial 2D grids. It simplifies usage by eliminating the need to manually create and connect points, making it easier to implement when applicable.

NavigationServer2D:
A powerful server API for finding the shortest path between two positions on an area defined by a navigation mesh. It is ideal for real-time 2D gameplay where actors must reach any position within a navigation mesh. Mesh-based navigation scales well with large game worlds, often requiring only a single polygon for a large area, unlike grid-based systems.

The NavigationServer2D manages navigation maps, each containing regions with navigation mesh data. Agents can be placed on maps for avoidance calculations. Communication with the server uses RIDs (Resource IDs) to reference internal maps, regions, and agents.

Available NavigationServer RID types:
- NavMap RID: References a specific navigation map that holds regions and agents. The map attempts to merge navigation meshes of nearby regions and synchronizes regions and agents each physics frame.
- NavRegion RID: References a specific navigation region containing navigation mesh data. Regions can be enabled/disabled or have their usage restricted via a navigation layer bitmask.
- NavLink RID: References a specific navigation link that connects two navigation mesh positions over arbitrary distances.
- NavAgent RID: References a specific avoidance agent, defined by a radius value.
- NavObstacle RID: References a specific avoidance obstacle used to affect and constrain the avoidance velocity of agents.

Scene tree nodes that assist with the NavigationServer2D API:

NavigationRegion2D Node:
Holds a NavigationPolygon resource defining a navigation mesh for NavigationServer2D. The region can be enabled/disabled, and its pathfinding use can be restricted by the ``navigation_layers`` bitmask. NavigationServer2D merges the navigation meshes of nearby regions into a combined mesh.

NavigationLink2D Node:
Connects two positions on navigation meshes over arbitrary distances for pathfinding. Links can be enabled/disabled, made one-way or bidirectional, and their pathfinding use restricted by the ``navigation_layers`` bitmask. Links inform pathfinding about connections and their costs, but agent movement logic requires custom scripting.

NavigationAgent2D Node:
A helper node that simplifies common NavigationServer2D API calls for pathfinding and avoidance. It should be used with a Node2D inheriting parent node.

NavigationObstacle2D Node:
Affects and constrains the avoidance velocity of avoidance-enabled agents. This node does not influence agent pathfinding; navigation meshes must be modified for that purpose.

2D navigation meshes are defined using the following resources:

NavigationPolygon Resource:
Holds 2D navigation mesh data. It includes polygon drawing tools for defining navigation areas in the editor or at runtime. The NavigationRegion2D node uses this resource to define its navigation area, and NavigationServer2D uses it to update individual region meshes. The TileSet Editor also utilizes this resource internally for defining tile navigation areas.
